player.seasonOutlook: Lee missed the entire 2018 season with a torn ACL and he's not expected to be back to full speed until August. Though the expectation is he'll return for Week 1, it's hard to invest much in a player who will miss so much of the offseason, not to mention one who has yet to finish a season better than 40th in fantasy points. Lee finished top 35 among wideouts in targets in both 2016 and 2017, but had more drops (12) than touchdowns (six) during the span. In fact, Lee has registered a grand total of eight touchdown receptions in 53 NFL games. The 27-year-old figures to lock down an every-down role once healthy, but he has a low ceiling in the Jaguars' run-first offense. He's only worth a late flier.

Boykin was the second of two wide receivers selected by Baltimore during April's draft. Unlike small and speedy first-rounder Marquise Brown, third-rounder Boykin stands 6-foot-4, 220 pounds and is a terrific athlete with serious length similar to Kenny Golladay. The Notre Dame product was a huge winner at the combine, posting outstanding marks in the 40-yard dash (4.42), three-cone drill (6.77), short shuttle (4.07) and broad jump (140 inches). Boykin doesn't add much after the catch (3.8 RAC last season), but he'll quickly be able to step in as a perimeter deep threat opposite Brown, with Willie Snead manning the slot. Baltimore's run-heavy attack and Lamar Jackson's shaky accuracy figure to crush his 2019 fantasy stock, but Boykin is an intriguing prospect, so stash him in dynasty.

Baltimore's D/ST has been a fantasy powerhouse for a long time, posting four top-seven campaigns the past five seasons and seven in the past 11 seasons. In 2018, the Ravens allowed a league-low 4,687 yards, and their 287 points allowed ranked second-best. On the other hand, the unit ranked 22nd in forced turnovers and was outside the top 10 in sacks for the fourth consecutive season. The worst news is that Baltimore lost its Nos. 1, 2, 5 and 7 snap-getters from 2018 (Eric Weddle, C.J. Mosley, Terrell Suggs, Za'Darius Smith). Earl Thomas was a strong addition, but this unit has more holes than we're used to. Expect a step back to more of a streaming option.

Believe it or not, the Steelers have led the NFL in sacks the past two seasons. They generated 52 last season to go with 99 tackles for loss (eighth-most) while allowing 5.3 yards per play (sixth-best) and blocking three kicks (second-most). Pittsburgh's D/ST salvaged an eighth-place fantasy season despite ranking 29th in forced turnovers (15), its lowest total since 2011 (15). Following minimal offseason turnover, Pittsburgh remains outstanding up front with T.J. Watt, Cameron Heyward, Stephon Tuitt and Javon Hargrave leading the way. The unit is suspect beyond that, though LB Devin Bush was scooped up in the first round of the draft, and Steven Nelson is an underrated addition at corner. This is a mid-pack D/ST option in 2019, though a Week 1 trip to New England hurts the draft appeal.

Goedert was the consensus top tight end in the 2018 draft, but landing with the Eagles in the second round meant learning the ropes behind target-hog Zach Ertz in the short term. Goedert was still on the field for a respectable 48 percent of the Eagles' offensive snaps but was limited to 2.7 targets per game and a 33-334-4 receiving line. He finished 20th in fantasy points but was 25th or worse in 10 of his 16 outings. The 24-year-old may see a slight boost in usage in 2019, but his ceiling is capped by the presence of Ertz, not to mention the acquisition of DeSean Jackson. Goedert has rare handcuff appeal for a tight end, however, and would be a TE1 lock in the event of an Ertz injury.

Everett took another step forward during his second NFL season, but the 2017 second-round pick has yet to emerge as a viable fantasy play. Stuck in a timeshare with Tyler Higbee in an offense heavy on three-wide-receiver sets, Everett was limited to 34 percent of the snaps and 3.1 targets per game last season. He was limited to two top-10 fantasy weeks, and 24 percent of his 49 targets were not catchable (second-highest). The Rams' high-scoring offense supplies Everett with some appeal in his third NFL season, but his situational role in Sean McVay's tight-end-unfriendly scheme limits him to a late flier in deep leagues.

Witten has come out of retirement and is back at the top of the depth chart in Dallas. When we last saw Witten, he was an every-down player and handled a solid 5.4 targets per game back in 2017. Primarily utilized as a sure-handed, short-area target who offers little after the catch, Witten finished 33rd at the position in fantasy points per snap. Of course, Witten led all tight ends with 897 snaps and, because volume is king, he managed a ninth-place finish in fantasy points. Witten is now 37 years old and expected to play more of a situational role in 2019. He hasn't posted a fantasy season better than ninth since 2013 and that's unlikely to change this season. He's a back-end TE2.

Moore was an unheralded seventh-round draft pick in 2017 and played sparingly during his first season and a half in the NFL. The East Central product took on a larger role near midseason in 2018 and went on to post a 26/445/5 line on 293 routes. Moore was primarily utilized as a vertical threat (his 15.4 aDOT ranked seventh), which allowed him a 17.1 YPR (fourth highest). Moore also racked up 11 end zone targets, which ranked 17th at the position. The 6-foot-2, 225-pound perimeter receiver will be hard to trust in Seattle's run-heavy offense, especially after the team drafted DK Metcalf, but Moore has some sleeper appeal due to Doug Baldwin's retirement.

Gabriel signed with the Bears last season and played a larger role than most anticipated. Gabriel caught 67 passes (25th most at the position) for 688 yards and a pair of touchdowns. His 72 percent catch rate was 14th best among receivers and marks the third season in a row in which he's finished no lower than the 75th percentile in the category. The sure-handed Gabriel has dropped one of 194 targets during the past three seasons. Gabriel's small frame (5-foot-8, 167 pounds) has led to only 17 end zone targets and 10 touchdowns in six seasons. The 28-year-old figures to open 2019 as Chicago's No. 2 receiver, but he'll be hard-pressed to fend off youngsters Anthony Miller and Riley Ridley as the season progresses. Gabriel has minimal fantasy upside.

Amendola's tour of the league continues with a stint in Detroit for at least the 2019 season. He was cut by Miami after posting a 59/575/1 line in 15 games last season. Amendola has never cleared four receiving touchdowns in a single season and has not finished a campaign with more than 689 receiving yards or better than 30th at the position in fantasy points (both came way back in 2010). Amendola has aligned in the slot on 83.3 percent of his career pass routes and work between perimeter receivers Kenny Golladay and Marvin Jones Jr in Detroit. Amendola figures to settle in third or fourth in line for targets in a run-first offense that ranked 23rd in offensive touchdowns last season. The 33-year-old is no more than a late-round flier in very deep PPR leagues.

Dalton threw 33 touchdowns and was fantasy's No. 6 scoring quarterback in 2013. Since that point, he's failed to clear 25 passing touchdowns in a season and hasn't finished a season better than 12th in fantasy points. That includes an injury-shortened 2018 campaign in which Dalton completed only 62 percent of his passes (ninth worst) and averaged 7.0 yards per attempt (10th worst). Dalton has posted exactly 99 rushing yards and zero touchdowns each of the past two seasons after rushing for 17 scores during the previous five seasons. Dalton is a below-average passer with a supporting cast that isn't much different than in 2018. Barring major contributions from new head coach Zac Taylor, Dalton is likely headed for another season of fantasy irrelevance.

Manning finished 2018 as the No. 17 scoring quarterback, which marked his first top 20 since 2015. Incredibly, the 38-year-old has posted one season better than 10th over the past 13 seasons. Manning has devolved into a conservative passer as he's ranked bottom 10 in aDOT each of the past two seasons. He isn't particularly efficient and offers very little with his legs with 37 rushing yards on 48 carries over the past three seasons. The Giants improved their offensive line, but swapped out Odell Beckham Jr. for Golden Tate during the offseason, which suggests New York is likely ticketed for a low-scoring, run-first offense heavy on short-area passing. Manning, who figures to defer some late-season starts to Daniel Jones, shouldn't be drafted in most formats.

Foles signed on with the Jaguars after a roller-coaster career that has fallen as low as him nearly retiring several years ago to as high as winning the Super Bowl LII MVP. Though Foles has flashed at times, he's never played more than 13 games in a single regular season and has finished one season better than 29th in fantasy points. Incredibly, Foles has registered exactly two weekly fantasy finishes better than 16th over the past three seasons. In seven games last season (including the playoffs), he tossed eight interceptions and fumbled four times. His 72 percent completion percentage was second best in the league, though his 6.8 aDOT was second lowest. Foles offers nothing with his legs, his supporting cast won't be nearly as strong in Jacksonville and the Jaguars operate a run-first offense. He shouldn't be drafted.

Flacco heads to Denver where he takes over as the Broncos' starter, though it's not clear that he's actually an upgrade on Case Keenum. Flacco posted the league's eighth-worst completion percentage (61 percent) and fifth-worst yards per attempt (6.5) in 2018. In fact, his 6.3 YPA over the past four seasons is worst among 38 qualified passers. Incredibly, Flacco has never finished a season better than 10th in fantasy points and his last finish better than 20th came in 2014. Flacco has struggled with efficiency for years, is now 34 years old, offers the bare minimum with his legs, has an unproven supporting cast and figures to lose some late-season starts to Drew Lock. Flacco is not worth drafting in most formats.

If you had to summarize Fitzpatrick's 2018 season in one aphorism, "YOLO" would be the appropriate choice. The veteran passer posted a 10.2 aDOT (third highest) and topped the NFL in both yards per completion (14.4) and yards per attempt (9.6). His 6.9 percent touchdown rate was third best and his 4.9 interception rate was the worst. During 28 games over the past three seasons, Fitzpatrick has thrown 36 touchdowns and 32 interceptions. The 36-year-old signed with Miami and will compete with fellow newcomer Josh Rosen for starting duties. The Miami supporting cast ranks as one of the worst in the league, though, so there is little fantasy value here in most formats.

Goodwin was one of fantasy's most popular sleepers last season, but injuries derailed his run at his first top-30 fantasy campaign. He patched together only six games in which he was on the field for at least two-thirds of the 49ers' offensive snaps. He posted a 15/314/3 line and ranked 30th in fantasy points during those weeks. One of the league's fastest players, the track star ranked in the top 10 in aDOT in both 2016 and 2017. His 17.2 YPR in 2017 was fourth highest in the league. Goodwin has appeared in 16 games once and at least 13 games twice in his six-year NFL career. Especially with Jimmy Garoppolo healthy, the 28-year-old Goodwin is a fine late-round, post-hype sleeper, but his path to snaps will be tougher with rookies Deebo Samuel and Jalen Hurd added to the fold.

Thomas signed with the Patriots, which breathes some life into a career that appeared to be closing in on the end. Since peaking with a 111/1619/11 line in 2014, Thomas' production has progressively dipped each of the past four seasons. He was shipped to Houston at last year's trade deadline before tearing an Achilles in December. The late-season injury suggests Thomas is a strong candidate for the PUP list, which would cost him the first six games of the 2019 regular season. The 31-year-old could find himself in the flex conversation if he lands a starting gig in New England's high-scoring offense, but his drop in production and injury make him no more than a late flier in deeper leagues. Definitely keep him on your watch list.

The 49ers drafted Hurd early in the third round of April's draft. Hurd is one of the biggest receivers in this class at 6-foot-5, 226 pounds. Despite his massive frame, Hurd was actually a running back who racked up 589 carries in three seasons at Tennessee before converting to slot receiver for one season at Baylor (48 carries, 107 targets in 2018). Hurd is obviously a very raw receiver, but his combination of versatility, athleticism and strength makes him an intriguing project. It's possible he quickly works his way up a wide-open 49ers depth chart, but Hurd is likely going to be a depth receiver as a rookie. Feel free to target him late in deeper leagues.

Yeldon signed with the Bills after not quite panning out in Jacksonville after the team selected him in the second round of the 2015 draft. With Leonard Fournette injured most of the season, Yeldon posted a career-best 22nd-place finish in fantasy points last season. He played a limited role as a rusher (104 carries), but finished top 12 in targets (76), receptions (55) and receiving yards (477), all of which were career-high marks. Yeldon has yet to hold up for a full 16-game season and has averaged a weak 4.0 YPC and 5.8 YPT in four NFL seasons. He's still in his prime at age 25, but will have a hard time finding touches alongside LeSean McCoy, Frank Gore and Devin Singletary in Buffalo.

The Washington defense ranked top-nine in interceptions (15), forced fumbles (19) and sacks (46) last season, but scoring one touchdown and ranking near mid-pack in yardage allowed (5,654) and points allowed (359) led them to a 16th-place finish in D/ST fantasy points. Landon Collins and first-round pick Montez Sweat are big-time additions, but gone are D.J. Swearinger, Ha-Ha Clinton-Dix, Preston Smith and Zach Brown, four of the team's top 10 defenders in snaps played last season. The likes of Josh Norman, Ryan Kerrigan, Daron Payne and Jonathan Allen supply this defense with some upside, but the Redskins have the look of a mediocre fantasy D/ST.

Baltimore selected Hurst in the first round of the 2018 draft, but the rookie played sparingly after missing the first month of the season with an injury. Hurst was limited to 106 pass routes and caught 13 of 23 targets for 163 yards and one touchdown. Hurst is an obvious candidate for a leap forward in his second NFL season, but he was outplayed by fellow second-year TE Mark Andrews in 2018, and Baltimore signed Nick Boyle to an extension to play a big role as a blocker. That leaves Hurst without a clear path to targets in the league's run-heaviest offense. Hurst, who turns 26 years old this year, is best as a dynasty hold.

The Bills drafted Knox in the third round of April's draft. He joins blocker Tyler Kroft to form a revamped TE duo in Buffalo. An intriguing pass-catching prospect, Knox essentially played wide receiver at Ole Miss, aligning in the slot on 80 percent of his 195 routes in 2018. Knox has terrific size (6-foot-4, 254 pounds) and athleticism, but isn't overly fast or quick. He was underutilized during his Ole Miss days, but was still highly efficient when targeted. He paced tight end prospects in YPR (18.9), aDOT (11.4) and first-down rate (80 percent) in 2018, while also averaging 8.7 yards after the catch (second best). Incredibly, Knox failed to catch a single touchdown in 22 games at Ole Miss. He may lead Bills tight ends in targets this season, but is unlikely to land on the fantasy radar.

The Redskins selected Haskins with the No. 15 overall pick in April's draft. The 6-foot-3, 231-pound pocket passer has a huge arm and throws an accurate ball, especially in the short area. Haskins posted a low-end 7.9 aDOT at Ohio State last season, though he made his passes count with a strong 70 percent completion rate and 50 touchdowns to only eight interceptions. Haskins offers very little as a rusher (108 rushing yards in 14 career starts, 5.04 40-yard dash), which means he will need to do his heavy lifting in fantasy with his arm. History suggests pocket quarterbacks are an extreme long shot for rookie-season fantasy relevance and Haskins could cede some early-season starts to Case Keenum. He shouldn't be drafted in season-long leagues.

The Chiefs posted their second consecutive mid-pack D/ST fantasy campaign last season, though their points came from specific locations. Kansas City allowed the ninth-most points (421) and second-most yardage (6,488) but ranked first in forced fumbles (23), first in sacks (52), second in D/ST touchdowns (five) and ninth in interceptions (15). Of course, both Justin Houston and Dee Ford were let go, and that star duo was responsible for 13 of the forced fumbles and 25 of the sacks. Frank Clark, Tyrann Mathieu, Alex Okafor, Darron Lee and Emmanuel Ogbah were added, but Houston and Ford were joined by fellow departures Eric Berry, Steven Nelson, Orlando Scandrick and Eric Murray. Tyreek Hill will add some value if he's on the roster (at least one return touchdown in each of his three NFL seasons), but this figures to be a weak D/ST option most weeks.

Dallas' D/ST finished as a mid-pack fantasy unit again last season and hasn't posted a campaign better than 14th since 2009. The perpetually mediocre unit finished 10th in forced fumbles (14), seventh in yards allowed (5,268) and sixth in points allowed (324) but was 26th in interceptions (nine) and 16th in sacks (39) while scoring only one touchdown. Adding Robert Quinn helps offset the loss of David Irving and likely Randy Gregory on the defensive line. This unit is not without holes but has plenty of star power in the forms of DeMarcus Lawrence, Jaylon Smith, Leighton Vander Esch, Sean Lee and Byron Jones, who supply some upside. The Dallas D/ST is a streaming option when the matchup is right, and that will be the case Weeks 1-3 (Giants, Redskins, Dolphins).

Looking for a deep D/ST sleeper in 2019? Arizona should be near the top of your list. The Cardinals' D/ST wasn't a particularly good fantasy bet last season, ranking 28th in forced turnovers (16), 26th in points allowed (425) and 19th in fantasy points (85). However, there is plenty of reason for optimism. The unit ranked fifth in sacks (49) and first in tackles for loss (118) last season before adding the likes of Terrell Suggs, Darius Philon, Jordan Hicks, Robert Alford, D.J. Swearinger and Byron Murphy to a group that includes Chandler Jones, Patrick Peterson and Budda Baker. Keep Arizona on your radar, especially with the Cardinals at home against Detroit in Week 1.
